pydantic_xlsx.doc:
In- and export data from and to Excel's xlsx files by using pydantic models.

Documentation

You currently can find the usage documentation in README file.

pydantic_xlsx.composition.doc:
pydantic-xlsx supports different kind of table/model compositions/structures. This can be one of the following cases:

  • Single Model Composition: The given pydantic schema doesn't contain any list of other Models. In this case the data will be exported into a single Sheet. The sheet will be named after the schema's title or (if not present) the class name of the model.
  • Root Collection Composition: The Model consists of a single __root__ property which is a list with instances of a model. The resulting document will contain a single sheet named after the title of the model. If the title is not present, the name of the model class (containing the __root__ property) will be used instead.
  • Collection Composition: The model consists of at least one list of model instances. There will be a sheet for each property (even for the properties which are not lists).

pydantic_xlsx.composition.Composition.doc: Base class for all supported composition cases. Learn more about this cases in the module documentation. The composition should be initialized via the CompositionFactory. This class also handles much of the heavy-lifting for the actual conversion between Excel Sheets and XlsxModels.

pydantic_xlsx.composition.Composition.sh.doc: Takes a XlsxModel and rearranges the data to exportable sheets.

pydantic_xlsx.composition.Composition.wo.doc: Takes a openpyxl Workbook and parses it to a XlsxModel.

pydantic_xlsx.composition.Composition.po.doc: Populates a given Excel worksheet with data and title.

pydantic_xlsx.composition.SingleModelCom.doc: The Model doesn't contain any lists of other Models thus will be exported in a single Sheet (named after the Schema title or if this is not present the Model class name.
Takes a XlsxModel and rearranges the data to exportable sheets.
Takes a openpyxl Workbook and parses it to a XlsxModel.

pydantic_xlsx.composition.RootCollection.doc: The Model consists of a single __root__ property which is a list of a Model. The document will contain a single sheet named after the title or if this is not present the name of the Model class the collection contains.
Takes a XlsxModel and rearranges the data to exportable sheets.
Takes a openpyxl Workbook and parses it to a XlsxModel.

pydantic_xlsx.composition.CollectionComp.doc: The model consists of at least one list of XlsxModel instances. There will be a sheet for each property.
Takes a XlsxModel and rearranges the data to exportable sheets.
Takes a openpyxl Workbook and parses it to a XlsxModel.

pydantic_xlsx.composition.CompositionFac.doc: Creates the correct Composition implementation based on the structure of a given model.
Creates and returns the correct Composition implementation for the given Model.

pydantic_xlsx.config.XlsxConfig.doc: Extends pydantic's config class with some Excel specific stuff.

pydantic_xlsx.config.XlsxConfig.header_f.doc: Font of the header row (first row). Defaults to: Font(name="Arial", bold=True).

pydantic_xlsx.config.XlsxConfig.font.doc: Font for the non header rows. Defaults to None.

pydantic_xlsx.config.XlsxConfig.header_a.doc: Optional alignment for the header cells. Defaults to None.

pydantic_xlsx.config.XlsxConfig.freeze_c.doc:
Define a cell coordinate where the cells should be freeze. The same value is used to calculate the rows and columns which should be repeated on each printed page. Defaults to A2 (header row (i.e. first row) stick to the top).

Per default this value is also used to calculate XlsxConfig.print_title_columns and XlsxConfig.print_title_rows (rows and columns which should repeated on each printed page)

pydantic_xlsx.config.XlsxConfig.ignore_a.doc: When true, additional row exceeding the models definition will be ignored when importing data from a existing xlsx file. The presence of such rows will otherwise lead to an validation error of pydantic. Use this option with caution.

pydantic_xlsx.config.XlsxConfig.disable_.doc: The library uses a primitive algorithm to set the width for each column based on number of chars of the longest cell content.

pydantic_xlsx.config.XlsxConfig.print_ho.doc: Whether to horizontally center the content when printing the document.

pydantic_xlsx.config.XlsxConfig.print_ve.doc: Whether to vertically center the content when printing the document.

pydantic_xlsx.config.XlsxConfig.print_ti.doc: Defines the range of columns which should be repeated on each page in the print out. Per default this is calculated based on the value of XlsxConfig.freeze_cell. To disable the feature set this property to an empty string (""). You can define individual column ranges using the format START_COLUMN:END_COLUMN. E.g. A:B will repeat the first two columns.

Defines the range of rows which should be repeated on each page in the print out. Per default this is calculated based on the value of XlsxConfig.freeze_cell. To disable the feature set this property to an empty string (""). You can define individual row ranges using the format START_ROW:END_ROW. E.g. 1:2 will repeat the first two rows.

pydantic_xlsx.conversion.doc: This module handles the representation of some additional types as a cell value in a xlsx file. It also provides the needed import functionality. This functionality should only be used for data types which need altering additional cell properties like number format. When only the value of a cell is altered there should be another way of implementing the needed functionality by using classes extending the primitive types which can be represented in a Excel cell.

pydantic_xlsx.conversion.Conversion.doc: Defines a type/class which a specific representation in the Xlsx file. Use the ConversionFactory to obtain the type class for your type.

pydantic_xlsx.conversion.Conversion.fiel.doc: Converts the content of the Excel cell into the type defined by the class. This value can then be used to populate the model field.

pydantic_xlsx.conversion.Conversion.popu.doc: Populates a given Xlsx cell with the with the given value. The representation of this value is defined by the Type subclass.

pydantic_xlsx.conversion.ConversionFacto.doc: Creates the correct Conversion implementation based on a given pydantic model field.
Determines based on a given pydantic Field (-type). If there is no implementation None will be returned.

pydantic_xlsx.fields.doc: Extends pydantic's fields with some extra functionality.

pydantic_xlsx.fields.XlsxFieldInfo.doc: Extends pydantic's Field class for some extra functionality (e.g. cell formatting).

pydantic_xlsx.fields.XlsxField.doc: A field for extra formatting etc. The styles defined by a field will be applied to the whole column.

pydantic_xlsx.fields.FieldTypeInfo.doc: Some XlsxField settings can be derived from certain field types like types.Money.

pydantic_xlsx.fields.MoneyFieldInfo.doc: Some XlsxField settings can be derived from certain field types like types.Money.

pydantic_xlsx.fields.FieldTypeInfoFactor.doc: Creates the correct FieldTypeInfo for a given type.
Creates and returns the correct FieldTypeInfo for a given type.
Same as from_field_type but directly calls FieldTypeInfo.field_info (if available) and returns the result.

pydantic_xlsx.model.XlsxModel.doc: Extends pydantic with the ability to in- and export data from/to xlsx files. The class also allows the usage of collection by using the __root__ parameter.

pydantic_xlsx.model.XlsxModel.__init__.doc:
Create a new model by parsing and validating input data from keyword arguments.

Raises ValidationError if the input data cannot be parsed to form a valid model.

pydantic_xlsx.model.XlsxModel.Config.doc: Extends pydantic's config class with some Excel specific stuff.

pydantic_xlsx.model.XlsxModel.to_file.doc: Saves the model to a Excel file.

pydantic_xlsx.money.doc: This module defines some frequently used currencies for convince.

pydantic_xlsx.types.doc: This module contains additional data types which are important when working with Excel data sources like a primitive Money type.

pydantic_xlsx.types.Money.doc:
Handles amounts of money by subclassing float. In general it's a very bad idea to store amounts of money as floats as all kind of funny things can happen. But as openpyxl parses currency cell values as int or float we have to work with it anyway.

Depending on the user input in the Excel file. The input float can have any number of decimal places. The value is rounded according to the number of minor units of the given currency and then converted to an integer.

To define a money field in your model you first have to define the currency you like to use. For this subclass the Money class and set some class variables:

class Euro(Money):
    minor_unit = 2
    code = "€"
    code_before_amount = False
    delimiter = ","
    thousands_separator = "."

pydantic_xlsx.types.Money.minor_unit.doc: Expresses the decimal relationship between the currency and it's minor unit. 1 means a ratio of 10:1, 2 equals to 100:1 and so on. For example the European currency "Euro" has a minor unit 2 as one Euro is made up of 100 cents.

pydantic_xlsx.types.Money.code.doc: Freely chosen code to represent your currency.

pydantic_xlsx.types.Money.delimiter.doc: Delimiter used to distinguish between the currency and it's minor unit.

pydantic_xlsx.types.Money.number_format.doc: Returns the Excel number format code for the currency.

pydantic_xlsx.types.Url.doc: A URL to a website with an optional title. Will be converted into a Excel Hyperlink.
